<subSubSection id="D9F16554FF9EBA32B71BF58DB6A7FC62" pageId="34" pageNumber="653" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="915436DFFF9EBA32B71BF58DB6A7FC62" blockId="34.[775,1367,552,979]" pageId="34" pageNumber="653">
<taxonomicName id="56EB4D5CFF9EBA32B71BF58DB194FCC0" authorityName="Stanley" authorityYear="2008" box="[777,946,749,782]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Mops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="653" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bakarii">Mops bakarii</taxonomicName>
is similar in most respects to 
<taxonomicName id="56EB4D5CFF9EBA32B71BF475B1C6FCF8" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1852" box="[777,992,789,822]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Mops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="653" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachypterus">M. brachypterus</taxonomicName>
, but is distinguished by its complete lack of basisphenoid pits, which are well to moderately developed in 
<taxonomicName id="56EB4D5CFF9EBA32B71BF4EFB1F3FC62" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1852" box="[777,981,911,940]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Mops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="653" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachypterus">M. brachypterus</taxonomicName>
. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
